      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Electricity Market</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Richard Hyse letter on Aug 27 article on electric power; holds deregulation of electric utilities in name of competition disregarded absence of sufficient number of suppliers that would make a free market possible</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Power: Get It While It Lasts'' (Week in Review, Aug. 27):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Power: Get It While It Lasts'' (Week in Review, Aug. 27):</p>
        <p>The deregulation of electric utilities in the name of competition disregarded the absence of a sufficient number of suppliers that would make a free market possible. Instead, as in the past, deregulation has empowered regional monopolization at the expense of consumers.</p>
        <p>The greatest danger to the economy is that rising energy costs will quickly inflate all prices, affecting low-income consumers the most. Therefore, protection of consumers by reregulation is our most urgent task. Price ceilings and subsidies for low-income consumers may temporarily ameliorate a situation that in the long run can be remedied only by accelerated construction of new,  large-scale generating capacity or by the new technology of fuel cells.</p>
        <p>RICHARD HYSE  Oswego, N.Y., Aug. 28, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is professor emeritus at SUNY-Oswego.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
